1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Nf3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 Bd6 7. g4 Nxg4 8. Rg1
Nxh2 {This acceptance of the Shabalov-Shirov gambit is absolutely logical and
one may wonder why it is not particularly popular in GMs' practice. As often
happens, the reasons are mostly historical. In 1992, at the dawn of the whole
system, White scored some convincing victories in this line (not at the
highest level, though), after which it was given up for long. Today we are
observing the process of rediscovering and developing it.} 9. Nxh2 Bxh2 10.
