{and} 21... Nxc5 22. Nxf4 gxf4 23. Bxf4+ Ka8 24. dxc5 Qxc5 25. Rae1 (25. Rad1
Qb4 $15) 25... Qd4 $15) 22. Nd7+ (22. Nxd4 Nxc5 (22... Qxc5)) 22... Rxd7 23.
Bxd7 Rf8 $17) (19. Qc2 Ned3 20. Nc5 (20. b3 Bxd4 21. Rab1 c5 $19 {and White's
position collapses.}) 20... Bxd4 21. Nd7+ Rxd7 22. Bxd7 Rf8 $17 {it is clear
that Black has more than enough compensation for an exchange - the Nd3 is
stronger than any R!}) 19... gxf4 20. Bxf4 Rxd4 (20... Qxd4 $5 {was also
possible. But I didn't have much time and decided that it was worth while to
keep the queens on the board - White's pieces are poorly coordinated and with
queens on the board he'll have more trouble keeping them together.}) 21. a5 $2
{In was worth keeping an option on opening the a-file after the forthcoming
c6-c5. The text move kills White's counterplay.} (21. Qe2 $5 Ka8 {/\Nd3} (21...
c5 $6 {allows a tactical shot:} 22. Nf6 $1 Rxf4 23. Qxe5+ Ka8 24. Qxf4 Qxe6 {
and it's hard to say who is better.}) 22. Bxe5 Bxe5 23. Nd2 Bg7 {and Black is
better.}) ({Better was} 21. Qg4 $142 Qc7 22. Qe2 Re8 23. Bg4 $1 c5 24. f3 $15 {
with a defendable position.}) 21... Qd8 ({Not so good is} 21... Rxd1 22. axb6
Rxa1 23. Rxa1 Ka8 24. Nc5 Nd3 25. Nxa6 $1 ({or even} 25. Nxd3 cxd3 26. Rd1 $13)
25... Nxf4 26. Nc5+ Kb8 27. Bg4 $5 {and White is not in any danger of losing.}
(27. Nd7+ Kc8 28. Bf5 Rd8 $13)) 22. Qe2 (22. Qg4 Qc7) 22... Re8 ({Simpler was} 
22... Ka8 $17 {, but I completely missed White's reply.}) 23. Rad1 $1 ({I had
counted only on} 23. Bf5 Rf8 24. g4 Ka8 $17) 23... Ka8 ({Black is losing after
} 23... Rxe6 24. Rxd4 Qxd4 25. Rd1 Qa7 26. Rd8+ Kc7 27. Qg4 Kxd8 28. Qxe6 Qd4
29. Qg8+) 24. Be3 {Being short of time and after just missing the counterplay
I chose the simplest continuation.} Rxd1 (24... Nd3 $1 25. Bxd4 Bxd4 26. Qg4 (
26. Bf5 c5) 26... c5 {was very strong, when Black's pieces are totally
dominating.}) 25. Rxd1 Nd3 26. Bf5 $2 ({I was more afraid of} 26. Nc5 Qe7 (
26... Qf6 27. Bd7 $5 (27. Rxd3 cxd3 28. Qxd3 Rd8 (28... Rxe6 $2 29. Qd7 {I saw
it during the game and was looking for an improvement, while my opponent was
thinking about his move.} Qe7 30. Qxe6 Qxe6 31. Nxe6 Bxb2 32. Bxh6 {and White
is not worse.}) 29. Nd7 c5 $19) 27... Rd8 28. b3 $13) (26... Qxa5 $6 27. Qh5)
27. Rxd3 cxd3 28. Qxd3 Bxb2 $1 {Only this computer suggestion leaves Black
with an advantage. Black is threatening the decisive Bb2-c1!} (28... Bc8 29.
Bxc8 Rxc8 30. g3 $13 {with full compensation} (30. b4 Rd8 31. Qc2 Bd4)) 29. Bg4
(29. Nd7 Qxe6 30. Nb6+ Kb8 31. Bf4+ Ka7 32. Be3 c5) (29. g3 Bc1 30. Bd4 Rd8)
29... Bc1) ({Also more stubborn was} 26. Qg4 Bd4 27. Qg6 (27. b3 Bxe3 28. fxe3
Qe7 29. Bf5 Ne5 $19) 27... Bxe3 28. fxe3 Qe7 29. Nd6 Rf8 $17) 26... Qd5 {Now
Black's pieces are totally dominating on the board and the rest is simple.} 27.
Qg4 (27. Ng3 c5) 27... Bxb2 28. h4 Bd4 (28... Rg8 {was also strong.}) ({I
decided not to allow any counterplay after} 28... c5 $6 29. Nxc5 Rg8 (29... h5
$1) 30. Qe4 ({or} 30. Nxb7 Rxg4 31. Bxg4) 30... Rxg2+ 31. Kxg2 Qg8+ 32. Kf3)
29. Bg6 Rg8 30. Bxd4 Qxd4 31. Qe6 Qd5 32. Qe7 c5 33. f3 ({Or} 33. Bf7 Qxe4 34.
Qxe4 Bxe4 35. Bxg8 c3 36. Bb3 c4 37. Bc2 b4) 33... Qd4+ 34. Kh1 Qg7 ({Avoiding
a last trap} 34... Rxg6 $2 35. Qe8+ Ka7 36. Qxg6 Bxe4 37. Qb6+ $1) 35. Qxg7
Rxg7 36. h5 b4 37. Kg1 Bxe4 {I was very pleased when this game was awarded the
prize for the best game of the Tal Memorial.} (37... Bxe4 38. Bxe4+ Kb8 39. g4
b3 {doesn't leave White much of a chance.}) 0-1

